The charts provide information about the public library in Little Chalfont, including the age distribution of library members, the breakdown of loans by category in 2016, and changes in the total number of loans between 2007 and 2016.

Overall, adults aged 18–64 constituted the largest proportion of library members, whereas those aged 65 and over represented the smallest group. In terms of borrowing categories, children’s and adult fiction dominated total loan figures. In addition, the total number of loans experienced an overall upward trend despite a slight dip in 2013.

Regarding the age distribution of members, adults aged 18–64 accounted for just over half of all library users, at 51%. Children represented 22% of members, while young adults aged 13–17 constituted 15% of the total membership. By contrast, people aged 65 and above made up the smallest proportion, at only 12%.

As for borrowing categories, children’s fiction and adult fiction were equally dominant, each accounting for 38% of total loans. Adult non-fiction represented a considerably smaller share at 13%, while children’s non-fiction made up just 6%. The remaining categories, namely children’s DVDs, young adult books and adult audiobooks, each accounted for only 1% to 2% of total borrowing.

The total number of loans showed an overall increase between 2007 and 2016. Borrowing rose steadily from approximately 16,000 loans in 2007 to just above 21,000 in 2011. Although the figure dipped slightly to around 19,500 in 2013, it rebounded afterwards and peaked at roughly 21,500 loans in 2016.
